entative government, articulates a notion of liberty or freedom as equal right as distinct from equal outcome, and discusses different kinds of liberties: personal, political, religious, and social. In search of a common truth or at least a common good, and analyzing what he perceives as the crisis of liberal democracies, Aron opens a space for reexamining the relation between liberty and equality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aDemocracyxPhilosophy. 0aEqualityxPhilosophy. 0aLibertyxPhilosophy. 0aRepresentative government and representationxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aCold War.  aConservatism.  aDemocratic Theory.  aEquality.  aFrench Thought.  aFrench political thought.  aHistory of Political Thought.  aLiberalism.  aLiberty.  aMark Lilla.  aPierre Manent.  aPolitical Philosophy.  aPolitical Theory.  aRaymond Aron.  aSocial Democracy.1 aLilla, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManent, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZeitlin, Samuel Garrett, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023 Englishz978311131922308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2023z9783111318646oZDB-23-DPH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311074974840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691250915?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691250915423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/doc